    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nStopping a process spawned by `vim.system` using `:kill()` or `uv.kill` results in descendants of that process getting orphaned. Presumably, the process group is not getting sent the termination signal. The same does not occur when using `jobstart`/`jobstop`\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nRun the following:\n```lua\nnvim -l - <<EOF\nlocal obj = vim.system({'bash', '-c', 'sleep 30 | sleep 30 | sleep 30'})\nvim.cmd(\"sleep 1\")\nobj:kill()\nvim.cmd(\"pgrep -f 'sleep 30'\")\nEOF\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe descendants should also be terminated, as in `jobstart`/`jobstop`\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-386+g858cd3d106\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux 6.19.9\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.16.1 (42f49eeb)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nAppImage",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "This is, at this point, the 5th case where we are solving problems in `vim.system` that were already solved in `jobstart()` and the internal `proc` layer. In this case, `os_proc_tree_kill` exists to deal with this, but `vim.spawn` doesn't use it.\n\nWe really need to have 1 job-control layer, not 2 parallel ones. That likely means `vim.spawn` should leverage the internal job-control layer where appropriate, rather than reinventing it via `vim.uv`.\n\nAnd there should be one \"job id\" namespace shared by `jobstart` and `vim.spawn`, so that `vim.spawn` can call `jobstop()` instead of using `uv.kill`: \n\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/26861",
